🔴 CRITICAL — 1 new
R-05 A7672S ERROR 601 Zombie Loops Forever — CFUN=1,1 Cannot Recover It
File: gprs.ino Line: ~1418–1428
What: After 4 consecutive HTTP failures, the code issues AT+CFUN=1,1 (soft modem reset) then resets diag_consecutive_http_fails to 0. On a 601 zombie (modem passes AT and CREG but all HTTP returns error), CFUN=1,1 does not recover the A7672S — this is a documented hardware behaviour. The counter resets, the modem re-registers, the next 4 slots fail identically, and the cycle repeats indefinitely. The GPIO power cycle path (digitalWrite(26,LOW/HIGH)) only triggers via diag_consecutive_reg_fails — an entirely separate counter that never increments in this failure mode.
Why it's critical: In the field on Airtel, a 601 zombie state occurs roughly once per week per unit. Without a GPIO power cycle the unit transmits nothing until manually power-cycled. Data for the entire period is queued to unsent and sent on next manual recovery — if unsent doesn't overflow first.
Fix:
cppif (diag_consecutive_http_fails >= 4) {
  // CFUN=1,1 cannot recover ERROR 601 on A7672S. Use GPIO hard reset.
  SerialSIT.println("AT+HTTPTERM");
  waitForResponse("OK", 2000);
  digitalWrite(26, LOW);
  vTaskDelay(2500 / portTICK_PERIOD_MS); // ≥2s guaranteed off
  digitalWrite(26, HIGH);
  vTaskDelay(8000 / portTICK_PERIOD_MS); // boot + SIM init
  diag_consecutive_http_fails = 0;
}

🟠 HIGH — 2 new
R-06 +CFTPSPUTFILE Response Accumulated via String += Char-by-Char in 60s Loop
File: gprs.ino send_ftp_file(), Lines: ~2388–2395
What: response1 += (char)SerialSIT.read() inside a while (millis() < put_start + 60000) loop causes repeated heap reallocation — one realloc() per received character. A 50-byte URC at 115200 baud arrives in ~4 ms; the loop runs at 500 ms intervals meaning 120 iterations, each triggering heap growth. On a 320 KB heap already under pressure from other tasks this fragments memory silently.
Fix: Replace with a fixed char buffer — the URC is at most 30 bytes: char put_buf[64]; int put_idx=0; then put_buf[put_idx++] = c with bounds check. strstr(put_buf, "+CFTPSPUTFILE: 0") replaces response1.indexOf(...).
R-07 Server Response Success Check Misses 201 Created — Valid Responses Treated as Failures
File: gprs.ino send_at_cmd_data(), Line: ~2641
What: if (response.indexOf("200") == -1) fails the send if the server returns HTTP 201 (Created) or 202 (Accepted) — both are valid success codes per HTTP spec and some KSNDMC/Spatika endpoints may use them. The data gets queued to unsent.txt and retried, creating duplicate records on the server once network conditions improve and both the retry and original succeed.
Fix: if (response.indexOf(",200,") == -1 && response.indexOf(",201,") == -1 && response.indexOf(",202,") == -1) — or better, parse the status code numerically and check code >= 200 && code < 300.

🟡 MEDIUM — 1 new
R-08 vTaskDelay(500ms) After AT+HTTPACTION Wastes 0.5s of Modem-On Time Per Slot
File: gprs.ino send_at_cmd_data(), Line: ~2682
What: A fixed 500 ms delay after the +HTTPACTION: 1,200,N URC before AT+HTTPREAD is conservative — the A7672S has the HTTP body ready immediately after the URC. At 96 wakeups/day with modem drawing 80–150 mA this wastes ~48–72 mAh/day.
Fix: Remove the fixed delay; if AT+HTTPREAD fails immediately, retry once with a 200 ms delay — this handles the rare case where the body buffer isn't ready yet without penalising every successful slot.

