🟠 HIGH — 2 new
R-09 send_health_report() Holds fsMutex for 5+ Seconds on BSNL — Scheduler Write Times Out
File: gprs.ino Lines: ~5112–5128
What: fsMutex is taken at entry (line ~5112) and held through the entire payload build. On BSNL, vTaskDelay(5000ms) fires immediately after take — before any file reads. At 11:00 AM the health report and the scheduler's 15-minute write compete for fsMutex. The scheduler's take has a 5 s timeout; the health report holds it for 5 s delay + AT silencing (~2 s) + SPIFFS reads (~200 ms) = ~7 s minimum. Scheduler times out, aborts the record write, and that slot's data is permanently lost — no retry, no queue.
Fix: Move the BSNL delay to before the fsMutex take. The breather is a modem settling time — it does not need filesystem protection.
cpp// BSNL breather BEFORE taking fsMutex
if (strstr(carrier, "BSNL")) vTaskDelay(5000 / portTICK_PERIOD_MS);
else vTaskDelay(1000 / portTICK_PERIOD_MS);

if (xSemaphoreTake(fsMutex, pdMS_TO_TICKS(5000)) != pdTRUE) { ... }
R-10 Scheduler 15-Min Slot Has No Protection Against Concurrent Health Report
File: scheduler.ino slot entry gate | AIO9_5.0.ino
What: health_in_progress only gates loop()'s sleep path — it does not block the scheduler from entering its 15-minute write block. Both the scheduler and send_health_report() can hold or contend fsMutex simultaneously on the hour (11:00, 12:00, 13:00). Even with the R-09 fix, the broader design has no explicit mutual exclusion between these two paths. On a BSNL station at 11:00 AM this collision is deterministic — it happens every health report day.
Fix: Set schedulerBusy = true before the fsMutex take in the scheduler write path (already done), and add a check in send_health_report() to defer if schedulerBusy is true:
cppbool send_health_report(bool useJitter) {
  if (schedulerBusy) {
    debugln("[Health] Deferring: scheduler mid-write.");
    return false; // will retry next slot
  }
  // ... existing mutex takes ...

🟡 MEDIUM — 2 new
R-11 tempHum Task Polls Every 5 s — LCD Update Latency Acceptable, But readHDC Holds i2cMutex Across Two Wire Transactions With a 20 ms Gap
File: tempHum.ino readHDC(), lines: ~trigger → release → delay(20ms) → re-acquire
What: The Phase 4 Fix correctly releases i2cMutex for the 20 ms conversion wait. However, between release and re-acquire there is a window where rtcRead or lcdkeypad can grab the mutex and initiate their own I2C transaction. If rtcRead reads the DS1307 during this window and the HDC sensor is mid-conversion, the HDC's I2C state machine is interrupted. On the HDC2022 this is benign (the conversion completes independently). On the HDC1080 the data register pointer resets on any bus activity — the subsequent requestFrom will read stale data from the last measurement, producing a reading that is correct in value but from one cycle ago. Not data loss, but a 5-second stale reading once per I2C collision. Field impact: negligible unless the station is used for sub-minute analysis.
R-12 printf() in parse_and_convert_clbs_response() Bypasses ota_silent_mode Guard
File: rtcRead.ino parse_and_convert_clbs_response(), lines with printf("Original GMT Time...")
What: printf() on ESP32 writes to UART0 (same physical pin as Serial). It bypasses the ota_silent_mode check in the debugln macro. During an OTA download, if resync_time() fires concurrently (RTC battery dead, badReads >= 24), the printf output will inject bytes into the modem's UART read buffer through the shared UART0, corrupting the firmware binary stream. On the A7672S, the OTA range-GET reads the modem UART directly — a few stray bytes at a 32 KB chunk boundary will cause Update.write() to fail with a checksum mismatch, aborting the OTA and leaving the device on the old firmware.
Fix: Replace both printf calls with debugf (which respects ota_silent_mode).

